The Netherlands Film Festival and the Netherlands Film Fund announced the Golden Film on [[September 4]], [[2001]] as an award for films from the Netherlands that had been seen by a paying audience of, at that time, 75,000 or more. The [[Platinum Film]] was introduced at the same time, for films with paying audiences of 200,000 or more. The first Golden Film was awarded on [[September 28]], [[2001]] to ''[[I Love You Too (film)|I Love You Too]]'' (2001),<ref name="iloveyoutoo">{{cite web
  | title = Gouden Film voor Ik ook van jou
  | work = [http://www.goudenfilm.nl/ www.goudenfilm.nl]
  | publisher = [[Netherlands Film Festival]] / [[Netherlands Film Fund]]
  | date = [[2001-09-28]]
  | url = http://www.goudenfilm.nl/films/ikookvanjou.html
  | accessdate = 2007-06-28 }} {{nl icon}}</ref> and by the end of 2002 a total of 10 Golden Films had been awarded.

Within 18 months of the award's introduction, the public's interest in [[Netherlands|Dutch]] films in the Netherlands had increased. The audience for Dutch films as a percentage of the total cinema audience in the Netherlands was 5.5% in 1999 and 5.9% in 2000. After the introduction of the award, audiences increased to 9.5% in 2001 and to 10.5% in 2002.<ref name="statistics"/>

In 2003, the criterion for the award was changed in an effort to further stimulate the Dutch film industry. Films released after [[January 1]], [[2003]] had to reach paying audiences of 100,000 to qualify for the Golden Film and 400,000 for the Platinum Film.<ref name="film-fund-press-release"/> All films that had received a Golden Film before 2003 would also have received a Golden Film under the new criterion.<ref name="report2001">{{cite web
  | title = NFC annual report 2001
  | work = [http://www.nfcstatistiek.nl/ www.nfcstatistiek.nl] 
  | publisher = Dutch Federation for Cinematography
  | date = [[2002]]
  | url = http://www.nfcstatistiek.nl/jv01.pdf
  | accessdate = 2007-11-04 }} {{nl icon}}</ref><ref name="report2002">{{cite web
  | title = NFC annual report 2002
  | work = [http://www.nfcstatistiek.nl/ www.nfcstatistiek.nl] 
  | publisher = Dutch Federation for Cinematography
  | date = [[2003]]
  | url = http://www.nfcstatistiek.nl/jv02.pdf
  | accessdate = 2007-10-21 }} {{nl icon}}</ref> From 2003 until 2006, the percentage of cinema visitors who watched a Dutch film was between 9.20% and 13.26%.<ref name="statistics"/>

Since its introduction, the Golden Film has been awarded to [[List of films that received the Golden Film|{{:List of films that received the Golden Film}}&nbsp;films]]. In 2004, nine films were awarded the Golden Film, the highest number to have received the award in a single year. Most of the films that are awarded the Golden Film have taken a week or more to reach the target audience figure. Only ''[[Full Moon Party (film)|Full Moon Party]]'' (2002) and ''[[Black Book (film)|Black Book]]'' (2006) have reached the criterion, for respectively 75,000 and {{nowrap|100,000 visitors}}, during their opening weekends.<ref>{{cite web
  | title = Volle Maan na openingsweekend al Gouden Film
  | work = [http://www.filmfocus,nl/ Filmfocus]
  | date = [[2002-10-14]]
  | url = http://www.filmfocus,nl/nieuws/3466-Volle-Maan-na-openingsweekend-al-Gouden-Film.html
  | accessdate = 2007-09-23 }} {{nl icon}}</ref><ref name="zwartboek">{{cite news 
  | title = 'Zwartboek' trekt in eerste weekend 125.000 bezoekers
  | work = [http://www.nrc.nl/ www.nrc.nl]
  | publisher = [[NRC Handelsblad]]
  | date = [[2006-09-18]]
  | url = http://www.nrc.nl/kunst/article484960.ece
  | accessdate = 2007-12-27 }} {{nl icon}}</ref>

==Response to the award==
Dutch newspapers, such as ''[[Algemeen Dagblad]]'',<ref name="bontekoe">{{cite news 
  | title = Gouden Film voor Bontekoe
  | work = [http://www.ad.nl/ www.ad.nl]
  | publisher = [[Algemeen Dagblad]]
  | date = [[2007-12-27]]
  | url = http://www.ad.nl/filmwereld/article1924125.ece
  | accessdate = 2007-12-27 }} {{nl icon}}</ref> ''[[De Telegraaf]]'',<ref name="verliefd"/> and ''[[NRC Handelsblad]]'',<ref name="zwartboek"/> report about films receiving the Golden Film. When the film ''[[De Scheepsjongens van Bontekoe]]'' (2007) had drawn {{nowrap|100,000 visitors}} to the cinema, the Dutch news agency [[Algemeen Nederlands Persbureau]] said the film had reached "the magical threshold of 100,000".{{ref label|anp_|i|i}}<ref name="bontekoe"/>

Recipients consider the Golden Film to be an award for success. Director [[Martin Koolhoven]] said, when ''[[Schnitzel Paradise]]'' (2005) received the award, that he did not expect his film to be such a success. ''Schnitzel Paradise'' was his first commercially successful film.<ref>{{cite web
  | title = Schnitzelparadijs krijgt Gouden Film
  | work = [http://www.cinema.nl/ Cinema.nl]
  | publisher = [[De Volkskrant]] / [[VPRO]]
  | date = [[2005-09-20]]
  | url = http://www.cinema.nl/cinema/magazines/news/index.jsp?portals=3142294&magazines=5268514&news=24152080
  | accessdate = 2007-09-22 }} {{nl icon}}</ref> Fifteen-year-old [[Sem Veeger]], lead actress in the film ''[[Keep Off]]'' (2006), said she knew that many people had seen the film, but she did not expect it to receive a Golden Film.<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Dammers
  | first = Maartje
  | title = Gouden Film voor Afblijven
  | work = [http://www.kidsweek.nl/ www.kidsweek.nl]
  | publisher = [[Kidsweek]]
  | date = [[2006-10-19]]
  | url = http://www.kidsweek.nl/artikel/171961/
  | accessdate = 2007-09-22 }} {{nl icon}}</ref>

Critics of the award have said that films which have sold only 75,000 or {{nowrap|100,000 tickets}} cannot be considered successful. In 2002, film journalist Ronald Ockhuysen said about the Golden Film:
<blockquote class="templatequote"><div>A good idea – in itself. (...) A positive signal towards the people. But it is doubtful whether the masses pick up the signal. 75,000&nbsp;visitors makes a meagre, a poor appearance. Especially for films solely made for the masses, like Full Moon Party. Johan Nijenhuis, the director of Full Moon Party, has admitted outright that he considers only 300,000&nbsp;visitors a failure.{{ref label|ockhuysen_|ii|ii}}<ref name="feest"/></div></blockquote> Ockhuysen also wrote that the Golden Film is a "child of our time" because it tries to reduce the value of a film to its commercial success, and it is supporting films that already have large publicity budgets instead of smaller and more vulnerable productions.<ref name="feest"/> Film producer [[Rob Houwer]] has said that he believes the Golden Film is the prize for a [[failure|flop]]. In 2005, when the criterion for the award had already been increased from 75,000 to 100,000&nbsp;visitors, he said in an interview:
<blockquote class="templatequote"><div>It is really nothing at all. A failure. It starts to be something for a producer when 350,000 or more cinema tickets are sold. It is incomprehensible why there are media reporting about this award. Why does everybody accept this nonsense?{{ref label|houwer_|iii|iii}}<ref name="nonsense">{{cite web
  | last = Ekker
  | first = Jan Pieter
  | coauthors = Ockhuysen, Ronald
  | title = 'Ik ben de trait-d'union'
  | work = [http://www.cinema.nl Cinema.nl]
  | date = [[2005-10-20]]
  | url = http://www.cinema.nl/cinema/magazines/news/index.jsp?portals=3142294&magazines=5268514&news=24510908
  | accessdate = 2007-01-11 }} {{nl icon}}</ref></div></blockquote>

Since the introduction of the Golden Film, the only Dutch film produced by Rob Houwer was ''[[Het Woeden der Gehele Wereld (film)|Het Woeden der Gehele Wereld]]'' (2006), which sold only 4,000 cinema tickets.<ref name="statistics"/>

==Notes==
<div class="references-small">
:*{{note label|anp_|i|i}} The phrase "the magical threshold of 100,000" is a translation of the [[Dutch language|Dutch]] phrase "de magische grens van 100.000" that was used by the [[Algemeen Nederlands Persbureau|ANP]].<ref name="bontekoe"/>
:*{{note label|ockhuysen_|ii|ii}} The original quotation of Ronald Ockhuysen in [[Dutch language|Dutch]]: "Een goed idee - op zichzelf. (...) 'Een positief signaal naar de mensen toe.' Alleen is het twijfelachtig of het grote publiek dat signaal wel oppikt. 75 Duizend bezoekers heeft iets schraals, iets armoedigs. Zeker als een film, zoals Volle Maan, louter en alleen is gemaakt voor een massapubliek. Johan Nijenhuis, regisseur van Volle Maan, heeft ruiterlijk toegegeven dat hij 300 duizend bezoekers als een mislukking beschouwt."<ref name="feest"/>
:*{{note label|houwer_|iii|iii}} The original quotation of [[Rob Houwer]] in [[Dutch language|Dutch]]: "Dat is echt helemaal niks. Een mislukking. Pas vanaf zo'n 350 duizend verkochte bioscoopkaartjes begint het voor de producent ergens op te lijken. Het is onbegrijpelijk dat de media over die prijs berichten. Waarom slikt iedereen deze ongein voor zoete koek?"<ref name="nonsense"/>
</div>

